{
  "explanation": "The defendant is a first-time offender whose crime is non-violent and driven by personal debt rather than malice. They have demonstrated an effort to rectify their actions by partially paying back the embezzled funds. While embezzlement of $25,000 constitutes a serious breach of professional trust and warrants punitive action, a lengthy prison sentence—such as the 10 years shouted by the disruptive spectator—is disproportionate and counterproductive. A shorter incarceration period of 6 months, likely followed by probation, strikes an appropriate balance. It provides adequate punishment and deterrence while allowing the defendant the opportunity to eventually return to the workforce and complete the restitution payments to the victim.",
  "verdict": 6
}
